sec.p:
The partial differential equations governing the fluid flow and heat transport are derived from conservation of mass, momentum, and energy. Momentum conservation is expressed by Darcy’s law which describes the groundwater flow in a confined aquifer as: 
						(1)v=−k̲μf(∇P+ρf·g·∇z)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$ \boldsymbol{v} = -\frac{\underline{k}}{\mu_{f}}(\nabla P + \rho_{f} \cdot g \cdot \nabla z)  $$ 
							\end{document}

where v is specific discharge (or Darcy velocity) (m s−1), k is hydraulic permeability tensor (m 2), μf is fluid dynamic viscosity (Pa s), P is hydraulic pressure (Pa), ρf is fluid density (kg m −3), g is gravity (m s −2), and z is depth (m) (where z is pointing vertically upward) (Clauser 2003). The equivalent hydraulic head h0 (m) and measured hydraulic head h (m) are given as: 
						(2)h0=Pρ0·g+zd\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$ h_{0} = \frac{P}{\rho_{0} \cdot g} + z_{d}  $$ 
							\end{document}

Corresponding pore water pressure is calculated by distribution of equivalent hydraulic head h0 (Eq.2) and depth zd as: 
						(4)P(zd,h0)=P0+∫0zdρf(zd)·g·(h0−zd)·dzd\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$ P(z_{d},h_{0}) = P_{0} + \int_{0}^{z_{d}} \rho_{f}(z_{d})\cdot g\cdot(h_{0}-z_{d})\cdot dz_{d}  $$ 
							\end{document}

The continuity equation expresses the conservation of mass as: 
						(5)0=∂(ϕ·ρf)/∂t+∇·(ρf·v)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$ 0 = \partial(\phi\cdot\rho_{f})/\partial t + \nabla\cdot(\rho_{f} \cdot\boldsymbol{v})  $$ 
							\end{document}

The equation for fluid flow is derived from Eqs. 1, 4, and 5 using the Oberbeck-Boussinesq approximation (Boussinesq 1903; Oberbeck 1879): 
						(6)ρf·g·(α+ϕ·β)∂h∂t=∇·ρf·g·k̲μf(∇h0+ρr·∇z)+W\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$ \rho_{f}\cdot g\cdot(\alpha + \phi\cdot\beta)\frac{\partial h}{\partial t} = \nabla\cdot\left[\frac{\rho_{f}\cdot g\cdot\underline{k}}{\mu_{f}}(\nabla h_{0} + \rho_{r}\cdot\nabla z)\right] + W  $$ 
							\end{document}

The heat transport equation is obtained by conservation of energy (Clauser 2003): 
						(7)(ρ·c)e∂T∂t=∇·(λe̲·∇T−(ρ·c)f·T·v)+H\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$ (\rho\cdot c)_{e} \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} = \nabla\cdot (\underline{\lambda_{e}}\cdot\nabla T - (\rho\cdot c)_{f}\cdot T\cdot\mathbf{v}) + H  $$ 
							\end{document}

where (ρ·c)e is the effective volumetric heat capacity of the saturated porous medium and the fluid (J m −3 K −1), T is temperature (°C), (ρ·c)f is fluid volumetric heat capacity (J m −3 K −1), λe̲\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								$\underline {\lambda _{e}}$
							\end{document} is the tensor of effective thermal conductivity (W m −1 K −1), and H the heat generation rate source term (W m −3).

Thermal power Pt (W) is evaluated using the bottom-hole temperatures T (°C) from the producers as: 
						(8)Pt=ρw·cp·ΔT·Q\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$ P_{t} = \rho_{w}\cdot c_{p} \cdot \Delta T \cdot Q  $$ 
							\end{document}

where ρw is water density (862 kg m −3), cp is specific heat capacity (constant value of 4510 J kg −1 K −1 for calculations), ΔT=T−80 is the temperature difference between the produced and injected water (K), and Q is the production flow rate (m 3 s −1). It is assumed that there is no temperature drop while the produced hot water is ascending through the cooler sections of the crust. For a binary plant working on organic rankine cycle (ORC) with bottom-hole temperature-dependent thermal efficiency ηt (Beardsmore et al. 2010), and accounting for the parasitic installation consumption Pic (W) by the pumps, electric power Pe (W) is evaluated as: 
						(9)Pe=(Pt·ηt)−Pic\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$\begin{array}{*{20}l} P_{e} &= (P_{t}\cdot\eta_{t}) - P_{ic} \end{array} $$ 
							\end{document}

A permeability of 10 −11 m 2 is used for the fractured zone in the models after several trials. Stimulation increases the permeability of Soultz granite from 10 −17 to 10 −15 m 2, and the main fracture has a permeability of 10 −13 m 2 (Vogt et al. 2012). With an i-p separation of 2000 m and a production flow rate of 100 L s −1, four models are run where fractured zone permeabilities vary between 10 −10 and 10 −13 m 2 with decreasing order of magnitude. Reservoir impedance i (Eq. 12) of an EGS should stay within the threshold of 100 kPa s L −1 to ensure its commercial feasibility (Clauser 2006). Defined as the pressure drop between injectors and producers divided by the production flow rate, it can be understood as the pressure difference necessary to circulate a certain fluid volume (Kolditz and Clauser 1998). 
						(12)i=p̄injector−p̄producerQ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								 $$ i = \frac{\bar{p}_{\text{injector}} - \bar{p}_{\text{producer}}}{Q}  $$ 
							\end{document}

where p̄=ρf·g·h̄\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
								$\bar {p} = \rho _{f}\cdot g\cdot \bar {h}$
							\end{document} is the average pressure (Pa) in the injector or the producer. The reservoir impedance values for the four models are given in Table 3. On comparing the values, the fractured zone permeabilities of 10 −10 and 10 −11 m 2 give a reservoir impedance below 100 kPa s L −1. A very high permeability of 10 −10 m 2 will yield more heat but following Freeze and Cherry (1979), a permeability of 10 −11 m 2 is assigned to the fractured zone.
						Table 3
